// 📦 SUMMARY
// This code builds: A simple Jenkins pipeline with three stages (test, build, deploy), each printing a message to indicate progress.
// Language/Platform: Jenkins Declarative Pipeline (Groovy syntax)
// What you'll learn: How to define stages, use `script` blocks, and structure a pipeline for CI/CD workflows.
// Outcome: When run, Jenkins will sequentially execute the "test", "build", and "deploy" stages, each echoing its purpose to the console log.
// Why this matters: This template helps beginners understand stage-based pipelines and can easily be expanded into real CI/CD processes.

// ------------------------------
// 🧩 PIPELINE DEFINITION
// ------------------------------
pipeline {
  agent any                                     // ✅ What it does: Uses any available Jenkins agent to run the pipeline.
                                               // 🧠 Why it matters: No restriction on specific agent, good for general-purpose pipelines.

  stages {
    // ------------------------------
    // 🧩 STAGE: Test
    // ------------------------------
    stage("test") {                             // ✅ What it does: Defines a stage named "test".
                                               // 🧠 Why it matters: Group related steps for testing here.
      steps {
        script {
          echo "Testing the application...."    // ✅ What it does: Prints a message to Jenkins console output.
          echo "Testing the triggering jenkinks Webhook added multibranch"                                     // 🧠 Why it matters: Placeholder for actual test commands like `mvn test` or `npm test`.
        }
      }
    }

    // ------------------------------
    // 🧩 STAGE: Build
    // ------------------------------
    stage("build") {                            // ✅ What it does: Defines a stage named "build".
                                               // 🧠 Why it matters: Where build logic such as `mvn package` or `docker build` would go.
      steps {
        script {
          echo "Building the application...."   // ✅ What it does: Prints a message as a placeholder for build steps.
                                               // 🧠 Why it matters: Keeps the stage flow visible during testing.
        }
      }
    }

    // ------------------------------
    // 🧩 STAGE: Deploy
    // ------------------------------
    stage("deploy") {                           // ✅ What it does: Defines a stage named "deploy".
                                               // 🧠 Why it matters: Reserve space for deployment logic such as `kubectl apply` or `ansible-playbook`.
      steps {
        script {
          echo "Deploying the application...."  // ✅ What it does: Prints deployment placeholder message.
                                               // 🧠 Why it matters: Shows where to insert actual deployment steps later.
        }
      }
    }
  }
}

// ------------------------------
// ▶️ HOW TO RUN / EXECUTE THIS CODE
// ------------------------------
// - Save this Jenkinsfile in your repository root.
// - Push changes to trigger a Jenkins job (or manually trigger it in Jenkins).
// - Watch console logs for:
//   🧪 "Testing the application...."
//   🔧 "Building the application...."
//   🚀 "Deploying the application...."

// ------------------------------
// ✅ NOTES / GOTCHAS / TIPS
// ------------------------------
// - Replace `echo` with actual commands as your pipeline evolves.
// - Using `script {}` blocks is optional for simple steps but allows advanced Groovy scripting.
// - For multi-agent workflows, you can assign `agent` per stage instead of globally.

